Thought_Process: Because admissions are final and companies that fill in Step 1 disappear, I should avoid applying first to a company where I have very low priority and will almost surely be rejected while it fills with someone else. If I apply to Company_B first, I am last in its priority and it will fill with Seeker_E (or Seeker_B) in Step 1, so I gain nothing and lose the chance to lock in a good alternative. If I apply to Company_E first, I am top priority there and can secure a permanent match in Step 1. Company_E is my 4th true choice, but it dominates the likely outcomes from starting at B/C/A, where I would be rejected and end up only able to apply later to a worse remaining option (most likely Company_D). Thus I rank Company_E first to guarantee it, then keep the remaining companies in true-preference order for any off-path contingencies.

Because admissions are final at each step, I should avoid applying first to a company where I have low priority and strong competition, since rejection there could leave me with only worse remaining options. If I apply to Company_A first, I am only 4th in their priority and will almost surely lose that seat to Seeker_E (who ranks A 3rd) or Seeker_D/A depending on who applies; meanwhile Company_C is the one firm where I am top priority, so applying there first guarantees I secure a top-3 true option immediately. After that, I rank remaining firms by true preference, since if I were rejected later I would want the best remaining available. This makes Company_C first (safe), then Company_A and Company_B next, followed by D and E.

Because admissions are final each step, I should avoid applying first to a company where I am unlikely to be the top-priority applicant among those who will apply in that step. If I apply to Company_B first, I lose to Seeker_E or Seeker_B (both higher priority and likely applicants), and then in Step 2 I cannot apply to Company_C because it will be filled by Seeker_B (who applies to C as their 3rd choice after being rejected at A and B). By applying to Company_C first, I am the highest-priority among the likely Step-1 applicants (Seeker_E applies to C but C prefers me over E), so I secure a final match at my #2 choice rather than risk being shut out of B and C and ending up at D/E/A.
